## Adding a New Tool to the Pi Agent Extension

### File Structure
```
.pi/extensions/home-assistant/
├── index.ts                    # Register tool here
├── tools/
│   ├── ha-<name>.ts           # Tool registration + dispatch (thin file)
│   └── ha-<name>/             # Sub-modules if >300 lines
│       ├── crud.ts            # list, get, create, update, delete
│       └── ...
└── lib/
    ├── types.ts               # Add shared types here
    ├── api.ts                 # REST helpers: haGet, haPost, haDelete
    ├── ws.ts                  # WebSocket: wsCommand(type, data)
    └── format.ts              # Formatting utils
```

### Tool Registration Pattern (in tool file)
```typescript
import { Tool } from "@anthropic/sdk";
import { wsCommand } from "../lib/ws.js";
import { haGet, haPost } from "../lib/api.js";

export const tool: Tool = {
  name: "ha_<name>",
  description: "...",
  input_schema: { type: "object", properties: { action: { type: "string", enum: [...] }, ... } }
};

export async function handler(input: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<string> {
  const action = input.action as string;
  switch (action) {
    case "list": return await list(input);
    // ...
  }
}
```

### Register in index.ts
```typescript
import { tool as <name>Tool, handler as <name>Handler } from "./tools/ha-<name>.js";
// Add to tools array and handler map
```

### Conventions
- **< 300 lines per file** — split into sub-modules if larger
- **Action-based dispatch** — every tool uses `action` as first parameter
- **Consistent output formatting** — use format.ts helpers (timeSince, slugify)
- **Error handling** — catch and return readable error messages, don't throw
- **WebSocket for registry/collection ops** — use `wsCommand()`
- **REST for service calls** — use `haPost("/api/services/<domain>/<service>", data)`
- **Types in lib/types.ts** — shared interfaces, don't duplicate

## WebSocket Collection CRUD Pattern

Many HA features store data as collections with standard WS commands:

### Command Naming Convention
```
<domain>/list     → list all items
<domain>/create   → create new item (returns item with id)
<domain>/update   → update by id
<domain>/delete   → delete by id
```

### Examples by Domain
| Domain | WS Type Prefix | Storage |
|--------|---------------|---------|
| Tags | `tag/list`, `tag/create`, `tag/update`, `tag/delete` | `.storage/tag` |
| Zones | Collection helper via `config/zone` | `.storage/zone` |
| People | Collection helper via `config/person` | `.storage/person` |
| Categories | `config/category_registry/list`, `.../create`, `.../update`, `.../delete` | `.storage/core.category_registry` |
| Shopping List | `shopping_list/items`, `.../add`, `.../update`, `.../remove`, `.../clear` | `.storage/shopping_list` |

### Implementation Template
```typescript
async function list(): Promise<string> {
  const result = await wsCommand("<domain>/list");
  // Format and return
}

async function create(input: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<string> {
  const result = await wsCommand("<domain>/create", {
    name: input.name,
    // ... fields
  });
  return `Created: ${result.id}`;
}

async function update(input: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<string> {
  await wsCommand("<domain>/update", { id: input.id, ...fields });
  return `Updated: ${input.id}`;
}

async function remove(input: Record<string, unknown>): Promise<string> {
  await wsCommand("<domain>/delete", { id: input.id });
  return `Deleted: ${input.id}`;
}
```

### Key Notes
- WS commands return results directly (no HTTP status codes)
- Collection items always have an `id` field
- Some collections support `subscribe` for real-time updates
- Person and Zone use the collection helper backend pattern (see `lib/backends/`)
- Tags are standalone WS commands (not config/ prefixed)

## HA REST API Patterns

### Service Calls
```typescript
// POST /api/services/<domain>/<service>
await haPost("/api/services/scene/turn_on", { entity_id: "scene.movie_time" });
await haPost("/api/services/script/turn_on", { entity_id: "script.morning_routine" });
await haPost("/api/services/persistent_notification/create", { message: "Hello", title: "Alert" });
```

### State Queries
```typescript
// GET /api/states — all states
// GET /api/states/<entity_id> — single entity
const state = await haGet("/api/states/script.morning_routine");
```

### Error Log
```typescript
// GET /api/error_log — plain text system log
const log = await haGet("/api/error_log");
```

### Config Validation
```typescript
// POST /api/config/core/check_config
const result = await haPost("/api/config/core/check_config");
```

### Key Endpoints
| Method | Path | Purpose |
|--------|------|---------|
| GET | `/api/states` | All entity states |
| GET | `/api/error_log` | System error log (plain text) |
| GET | `/api/config` | Core configuration |
| POST | `/api/services/<domain>/<service>` | Call a service |
| POST | `/api/events/<event_type>` | Fire an event |
| GET | `/api/history/period/<timestamp>` | State history |
| GET | `/api/logbook/<timestamp>` | Logbook entries |

## Pre-Mutation Backup Pattern

Every write/update/delete action MUST snapshot the current state before applying changes.

### Import
```typescript
import { backupBeforeMutation } from "../lib/mutation-log.js";
// or from "../../lib/mutation-log.js" for subdirectory tools
```

### Usage — when current state is fetchable
```typescript
// Before the mutation call, wrap in try/catch (best-effort, never block the mutation)
try {
  const current = await wsCommand("config/entity_registry/get", { entity_id: entityId });
  backupBeforeMutation("ha_entities", "update", entityId, current);
} catch { /* best-effort */ }

// Now do the actual mutation
const result = await wsCommand("config/entity_registry/update", updateData);
```

### Usage — when using list to find current state
```typescript
try {
  const items = await wsCommand<WSArea[]>("config/area_registry/list");
  const current = items.find((a) => a.area_id === areaId);
  if (current) backupBeforeMutation("ha_areas", "update-area", areaId, current);
} catch { /* best-effort */ }
```

### Usage — when no get API exists (log the mutation params)
```typescript
backupBeforeMutation("ha_recorder", "adjust", statisticId, data, `Adjust sum by ${value}`);
```

### Parameters
```typescript
backupBeforeMutation(
  tool: string,      // Tool name: "ha_entities", "ha_yaml", etc.
  action: string,    // Action: "update", "delete", "rename", etc.
  target: string,    // Target ID: entity_id, device_id, area_id, etc.
  state: unknown,    // Current state object to snapshot
  summary?: string   // Optional human-readable summary
): string            // Returns backup filename
```

### Rules
1. **Always best-effort** — wrap in try/catch, never let backup failure block the actual mutation
2. **Snapshot BEFORE the mutation** — not after
3. **Use the most specific get API** available (get > list+find > log params)
4. **For delete actions** — snapshot inside the confirm block, after confirm check but before the actual delete
5. **For tools with existing state** (e.g. automations that fetch existing config for merge) — reuse that fetched state, no extra API call needed
